body: Added @nicolasnoble and @muxi as reviewers: both will need to approve.
I have verified that it does,  but would love to add the iOS build into CI if someone can help me understand how to add it.
Hi all,  What else is needed to get this in?
@nicolasnoble can you approve?
Ping.  Let me know if there is more needed from my side.

Thanks Nicolas.  https://github.com/grpc/grpc/pull/13016 was pull into 1.6.x branch.  What is good way for this to be in next release?  Not sure if its 1.7.x or 1.6.x branch.  Either is fine but would love it to be in  next major release.
Please backport into v1.7.x

```
[trickle] No significant performance differences
```
ok This says some build failures.  How do I see what failed?

Found that this messes with linux build because ios_cpu is set to x86_64 by default.

--ios_cpu=<a string> default: "x86_64"
Specifies to target CPU of iOS compilation.

This needs more work :(
Ping.  Also fixed the android config.

```
[trickle] No significant performance differences
```

@spinorx - Could you let us know the reason for the Android fix? This repo does not build Android code, which are captured by grpc-java. Also, since the previous commit was overriten (I guess you did a forced push?), could you let us know the difference between b96287a and previous fix? Thanks!

Thanks for taking a look.  Sorry that older copy was lost.  I am still trying to figure out best practices around GitHub pull request.  Is it better to do another commit rather than amend?

1) Difference between previous fix and current fix is that earlier I was using
```
values = {"ios_cpu": "x86_64"},
```
This does not work because iOS_cpu is set to x86_64 by default by bazel causing ALL (inc linux) builds to inherit darwin settings.  (https://docs.bazel.build/versions/master/command-line-reference.html look for ios_cpu). Now i moved to:
 ```
values = {"cpu": "ios_x86_64"},
```
which is set only for iOS builds (search experimental_enable_objc_cc_deps in  https://docs.bazel.build/versions/master/command-line-reference.html).
This time I tested iOS, android and linux all 3.

2) I am using same grpc C++ library on android (through ini) and iOS.  This allows me to write 90% of model code in C++ and only write UI code in java/swift.  Hope that helps.  Happy to answer any more questions on this.

Yea just pushing new commits should be fine. About your changes:

1. I see. That makes sense and looks good to me.
2. I am going to let @nicolasnoble to make another review on this. Note that is not officially supported by us for now, but it is good to know that you tried it. Could you let us know how it goes?

The Android changes are fine. Maybe I'd like to see a comment in the selector or something that points at the fac this isn't officially supported, since we don't have continuous integration testing for it.

Added the comment that this is not supported.

@muxi I just tried on android device,  It gives UNAVILABLE (14) status code.  iOS device works fine.  Not yet sure what the issue is.
@spinorx thank you. Please add comment to the iOS portion as well. Both sides are not supported for now.

```
[trickle] No significant performance differences
```
Thanks @muxi  Added comment for iOS too.  Is this way of stacking changes (instead of push -f)  better?

Yes that is better for me to look through what is changed. Thanks!

Running the last time of tests and will merge thereafter.
